[]: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by Azathoth &raquo; Tue Nov 30, 2010 11:37 am And on a completely different note from that, in response to my earlier one-liner about mother-figures: Reichu wrote: Kaworu is associated with both mothers and fathers. I&#39;ll be the first to vouch for the mom thing &#40;heck, for all I know I -was- the first; getting burned at the stake at ANF... GOOD TIMES!&#41;, but the Gendo connection is so blatant I&#39;m sure you can spot all the relevant cues without my help. :3 What&#39;s more, Kaworu is thoroughly linked to Kaji, whom Shinji&#39;s been known to look up to as a male role model. Yeah, there are SOME links to Misato, but not enough exclusive ones to warrant the leaps required to justify her being the genetic donor. Kaworu looks a lot more like a Lilin than the one known parent -- Adam -- so we can probably guess that he bears a very close resemblance to the donor. Also, since Kaworu is ostensibly male, and Adam logically is not, the donor must be male &#40;unless Misato has some chromosomal defect she hasn&#39;t told us about&#41;. The &quot;Misato&quot; thing just doesn&#39;t wash: wrong sex, no resemblance, and why would they use a kid for the donor anyway? I know Misato&#39;s age at the time &#40;not-exactly-14&#41; gets brought up a lot as &quot;evidence&quot; &#40;14-year-old pilots and all&#41;, but this is pretty flimsy on its own. Misato&#39;s mere presence acting as &quot;reasonable suspicion&quot; &#40;as cited in that Rei&#39;s Soul thread&#41; doesn&#39;t really work, either. We have a concrete precedent in the show for &quot;bring your kid to work and traumatize them for life day&quot; with Yui and Shinji. Also, adult test subjects are used in both other contact experiments &#40;both scientist-parents of main characters&#41;. &#40;If there is any logical association between the eventual use of teenagers as pilots in Project E -- after failed synchro-whatever experiments using adults --, and the KatsExp&#39;s molestation of Adam in 2000, I&#39;d like to hear it.&#41; If you want to &quot;pick a donor&quot; based on neat thematic alignments, Dr. K is your best bet, to be perfectly honest. There are so many connections that people would be chocking it up to Anno&#39;s genius or something if only he&#39;d included the minuscule additional amount of writing necessary to indicate that he gave even the slightest damn about who the donor was. &#40;And it&#39;s a pity he didn&#39;t, since it would have followed up Misato&#39;s character development in #12 oh so nicely.&#41;

